LOW|cmd/atcr/autofix_test.go:921|TestRunAutoFix_NilSandboxWithoutOptOutRefuses (the fail-closed proof for AC1) asserts only require.Error and a reverted tree, never pinning the error to the guard's specific message. Both signals could be satisfied by an unrelated earlier failure (e.g. a future refactor making ApplyPatch reject the input), so the test could pass for the wrong reason and would not catch the default fail-closed arm being silently removed as long as some earlier error still fires. Not a live false-pass today (inputs match the sibling passing test) but a robustness gap in a security-critical test.|Add require.Contains(t, err.Error(), "refusing") (or "unsandboxed"/"--no-sandbox") after the existing assertions to bind the check to the guard's message. Verify by temporarily deleting the default: arm; the test must then fail on the message assertion, not merely tree state.|testing|5|cmd/atcr/autofix_test.go:903-926|claude
LOW|internal/sandbox/docker.go:236|DockerBackend.Run folds context.Canceled into TimedOut (res.TimedOut=true, ExitCode=124). In the narrow race where the workload exits 0 and the parent context becomes cancelled before the runCtx.Err() read, a genuinely-successful run is now reported as a timeout; the old ==DeadlineExceeded check reported exit 0. Impact is minimal (microsecond window, cancelled caller discards the result) and the fold is the epic's intended behavior, so this is a documented nuance rather than a regression.|If distinguishing a real success matters, gate the fold on runErr != nil so only non-clean exits reclassify: if runErr != nil AND (errors.Is(runCtx.Err(), DeadlineExceeded) OR errors.Is(runCtx.Err(), Canceled)). Weigh against epic 32.2 Task 2 intent (Canceled to TimedOut) first. Verify with a fast fake run exiting 0 plus immediate parent cancel asserting ExitCode==0, TimedOut==false.|correctness|30|internal/sandbox/docker.go:219-249|claude
